article.description:
Georgia Schweitzer, filling in for injured starter Svetlana Abrosimova, scored a career-high 17 points as the
Minnesota Lynx beat the Seattle Storm 73-60 Sunday.
article.headline: Storm suffer setback in race for playoffs
article.linkText: Schweitzer helps Lynx dampen Storm's hopes
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Georgia Schweitzer, filling in for injured
starter Svetlana Abrosimova, scored a career-high 17 points as the
Minnesota Lynx beat the Seattle Storm 73-60 Sunday.

	   "I told our players, 'Don't be surprised if she comes out and
proves she should have been starting all year,' '' Seattle coach Lin Dunn said.

	   Schweitzer scored 13 points in the first half, one shy of her
previous career-high, on 5-of-7 shooting.

	   "I feel like I've been struggling with my shooting so it felt
good to make some shots,'' Schweitzer said. "We also did a good
job of passing and playing team basketball -- I got great looks out
there.''

	   The Lynx improved to 5-4 with Schweitzer in the starting lineup,
and are 4-15 when she is a reserve. Schweitzer had not started in
16 games before Sunday.

	   Abrosimova sat out because of a strained back.

	   Katie Smith also scored 17 points for Minnesota, which has won
two straight.

	   Lauren Jackson led the Storm (15-14) with 19 points. With three
games left in the season, fifth-place Seattle is trying to advance
into a Western Conference playoff spot. The top four teams qualify
for the postseason.

	   Sunday's game was the Storm's seventh in seven different cities
in 12 days.

	   "We were tired out there,'' Jackson said. "They came out
firing and played really well.''

	   The Lynx (9-19) used a 12-0 run midway through the first half,
holding Seattle scoreless for more than five minutes, to break open
a close game.

	   "That set the tone,'' Storm guard Sue Bird said. "We did not
play well, they did. The early lead gave them a lot of confidence.
That's big in this game.''

	   Tamara Moore keyed the streak with a pair of driving layups, and
Kristi Harrower capped the rally with a stop-and-go drive to the
basket for a 21-10 Minnesota lead.

	   Bird, Seattle's second-leading scorer, was held scoreless until
making a pair of free throws with 1:27 left in the first half. Bird
hit a halfcourt shot at the buzzer to cut Minnesota's lead to 37-30
at the break.

	   Smith made two 3-pointers, and Schweitzer hit a breakaway
basket during an 8-0 run early in the second half.

	   The Lynx took a 65-44 lead when Michele Van Gorp and Tamika
Williams made consecutive baskets.

	   "This is a game of emotions, a game of energy, a game of runs
and momentum,'' Lynx coach Heidi VanDerveer said. "It seemed like
when we got the lead, we weren't ready to give it up.''
